We have, <br><br>$$f(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {{{\sin 2x} \over {5x}},} &amp; {x \ne 0}  \cr 
   {{2 \over {15}},} &amp; {x = 0}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>at x = 0<br><br>$$\mathop {\lim }\limits_{x \to 0} f(x) = \mathop {\lim }\limits_{x \to 0} {{\sin 2x \times 2} \over {5x \times 2}} = {2 \over 5}$$<br><br>$$f(0) = {2 \over {15}}$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$\mathop {\lim }\limits_{x \to 0} f(x) \ne f(0)$$<br><br>at x = 0 function is discontinuous.

a, b and c are coplanar if $$[a\,b\,c] = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow \left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 1  \cr 
   2 &amp; 3 &amp; 2  \cr 
   1 &amp; m &amp; n  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow 1(3n - 2m) + 1(2n - 2) + 1(2m - 3) = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow 5n - 5 = 0$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ n = 1<br><br>Now, $$c = \widehat i + m\widehat j + \widehat k$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow \left| c \right| = \sqrt {{1^2} + {m^2}{{(1)}^2}}  = \sqrt 6 $$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow \sqrt {{m^2} + 2}  = \sqrt 6  \Rightarrow {m^2} - 6 - 2 = 4$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$m =  \pm \,2$$

